answer:
Primitive values hold a single value. To store collections of values, JavaScript uses non-primitive types — everything that isn't a primitive is, broadly speaking, an object.

Object — a collection of key/value pairs:

var obj1 = {
  x: 43,
  y: "Hello world!",
  z: function() { return this.x; }
};

Array — an ordered, indexed collection. Under the hood, arrays are also objects:

var array1 = [5, "Hello", true, 4.1];

Functions, dates, regular expressions, maps, sets, and class instances are all object types as well.

Implicit coercion is the automatic conversion of a value from one type to another that JavaScript performs when an operator is applied to operands of different types.

String coercion happens with the + operator. If either operand is a string, the other is converted to a string and the two are concatenated:

var x = 3;
var y = "3";
x + y;  // "33"

var a = 24;
var b = "Hello";
a + b;  // "24Hello"

Note that + concatenates only when at least one operand is a string. With two numbers it adds:

var name = "Vivek";
var surname = " Bisht";
name + surname;  // "Vivek Bisht"

Other arithmetic operators (-, *, /, %) coerce strings to numbers instead:

var x = 3;
var y = "3";
x - y;  // 0

Boolean coercion happens with logical operators, ternaries, if statements, and loop conditions. Values are categorized as truthy or falsy. The falsy values are: false, 0, -0, 0n, "", null, undefined, and NaN. Everything else is truthy.

var x = 0;
var y = 23;
if (x) { console.log(x); }  // does not run — x is falsy
if (y) { console.log(y); }  // runs — y is truthy

The logical operators in JavaScript don't return a boolean — they return one of the operands:

|| (OR): returns the first truthy operand, or the last operand if none are truthy.
&& (AND): returns the first falsy operand, or the last operand if all are truthy.

var x = 220, y = "Hello", z = undefined;
x || y;  // 220
x || z;  // 220
x && y;  // "Hello"
y && z;  // undefined

Equality coercion happens with ==. Unlike ===, == converts both operands to a common type before comparing:

var a = 12;
var b = "12";
a == b;   // true  — b is coerced to a number
a === b;  // false — different types

In JavaScript, primitive values are effectively passed by value and objects are passed by reference (more precisely: the reference itself is passed by value).

Consider what happens when you assign a value to a variable:

var x = 2;

The right-hand side allocates a slot in memory holding the value 2, and x is bound to that slot.

With primitives, assigning one variable to another copies the value into a new slot:

var y = 234;
var z = y;
y = 23;
console.log(z);  // 234 — z has its own copy

With objects, assignment copies the reference, not the underlying data, so both variables point at the same object:

var obj1 = { name: "Vivek", surname: "Bisht" };
var obj2 = obj1;
obj1.name = "Akki";
console.log(obj2);  // { name: "Akki", surname: "Bisht" }

Reassigning obj1 to a brand-new object, however, doesn't affect obj2 — it just rebinds the obj1 variable. This is why JavaScript is sometimes described as "pass by sharing": you can mutate a shared object, but you can't make the caller's variable point at something new.

An IIFE (pronounced "iffy") is a function that is defined and invoked in the same expression. The classic syntax is:

(function () {
  // do something
})();

There are two sets of parentheses, each serving a purpose:

The outer pair wraps the function so the parser treats it as a function expression rather than a function declaration. Without it, the engine would expect a name after the function keyword and throw a syntax error.

The trailing pair invokes the resulting function immediately. Without it, you'd just have a function expression that is never called.

Historically, IIFEs were a popular way to create a private scope and avoid polluting the global namespace. With ES6 block-scoped let/const and ES modules, they are less common today but still occasionally useful.

A higher-order function is one that either takes another function as an argument, returns a function as a result, or both. This is possible because functions in JavaScript are first-class citizens — they can be assigned to variables, passed around, and returned, like any other value.

Examples:

function higherOrder(fn) {
  fn();
}
higherOrder(function () { console.log("Hello world"); });

function higherOrder2() {
  return function () {
    return "Do something";
  };
}
var x = higherOrder2();
x();  // "Do something"

Built-in array methods like map, filter, reduce, forEach, and sort are all higher-order: each one accepts a callback that decides how to transform or combine the elements.

this refers to the object that the function is being called on. Its value is determined at call time, not at definition time, by how the function is invoked.

Example 1 — called as a standalone function:

function doSomething() { console.log(this); }
doSomething();

In a browser, this logs the global object (window) in non-strict mode and undefined in strict mode, because the call has no explicit receiver.

Example 2 — called as a method:

var obj = {
  name: "vivek",
  getName: function () { console.log(this.name); }
};
obj.getName();  // "vivek"

Here this is obj because the function was invoked through obj.

Example 3 — same function, different receiver:

var obj = { name: "vivek", getName: function () { console.log(this.name); } };
var getName = obj.getName;
var obj2 = { name: "akshay", getName: getName };
obj2.getName();  // "akshay"

The function was defined on obj but invoked through obj2, so this is obj2.

A useful shortcut: look at what's to the left of the dot at the call site. Whatever is there is this. If there's nothing to the left of the dot, this is the global object (or undefined in strict mode).

Example 4 — missing property:

var obj1 = { address: "Mumbai,India", getAddress: function () { console.log(this.address); } };
var obj2 = { name: "akshay" };
obj2.getAddress = obj1.getAddress;
obj2.getAddress();  // undefined — obj2 has no address property

Arrow functions are the one exception: they don't bind their own this, but inherit it from the enclosing lexical scope. call, apply, and bind can also be used to set this explicitly.

A self-invoking function is one that is executed automatically as soon as it is defined, without being explicitly called from elsewhere. They are written as function expressions immediately followed by (), and they are the same thing as an IIFE:

(function () {
  console.log("runs immediately");
})();

A function declaration cannot invoke itself this way — only function expressions can. Self-invoking functions are typically anonymous and are used to create a private scope for some setup code that should run once and then disappear.

All three are methods on Function.prototype that let you control the value of this when calling a function.

call(): invokes the function with a given this value and arguments listed individually.

function sayHello() { return "Hello " + this.name; }
var obj = { name: "Sandy" };
sayHello.call(obj);  // "Hello Sandy"

It also lets one object borrow a method from another:

var person = { age: 23, getAge: function () { return this.age; } };
var person2 = { age: 54 };
person.getAge.call(person2);  // 54

call() accepts additional arguments after the this value:

function saySomething(message) { return this.name + " is " + message; }
var person4 = { name: "John" };
saySomething.call(person4, "awesome");  // "John is awesome"

apply(): identical to call(), except that the arguments are passed as a single array (or array-like object):

saySomething.apply(person4, ["awesome"]);  // "John is awesome"

bind(): does not invoke the function — it returns a new function with this permanently bound to the supplied object (and optionally with some arguments pre-filled):

var bikeDetails = {
  displayDetails: function (registrationNumber, brandName) {
    return this.name + ", bike details: " + registrationNumber + ", " + brandName;
  }
};
var person1 = { name: "Vivek" };
var detailsOfPerson1 = bikeDetails.displayDetails.bind(person1, "TS0122", "Bullet");
detailsOfPerson1();  // "Vivek, bike details: TS0122, Bullet"

Currying transforms a function that takes multiple arguments into a chain of functions that each take a single argument. A function f(a, b, c) becomes f(a)(b)(c).

Example of a manually curried function:

function add(a) {
  return function (b) {
    return a + b;
  };
}
add(3)(4);  // 7

And a small helper that curries any two-argument function:

function multiply(a, b) { return a * b; }
function currying(fn) {
  return function (a) {
    return function (b) {
      return fn(a, b);
    };
  };
}
var curriedMultiply = currying(multiply);
multiply(4, 3);          // 12
curriedMultiply(4)(3);   // 12

Currying doesn't change what a function does — only how it is called. It is useful for partial application: you can fix some of the arguments up front and reuse the resulting function later.

Scope determines which variables and functions are accessible from a given point in the code. JavaScript has three kinds of scope:

Global scope — anything declared outside any function or block is accessible from anywhere in the program:

var globalVariable = "Hello world";
function sendMessage() { return globalVariable; }
function sendMessage2() { return sendMessage(); }
sendMessage2();  // "Hello world"

Function scope — variables declared inside a function (with var, let, or const) are only visible inside that function:

function awesomeFunction() {
  var a = 2;
  var multiplyBy2 = function () { console.log(a * 2); };
}
console.log(a);     // ReferenceError
multiplyBy2();      // ReferenceError

Block scope — variables declared with let or const are only visible inside the enclosing block. var does not have block scope:

{ let x = 45; }
console.log(x);     // ReferenceError

for (let i = 0; i < 2; i++) { /* ... */ }
console.log(i);     // ReferenceError

Scope chain: when the engine looks up a name, it first checks the current scope, then the enclosing scope, then the next enclosing scope, and so on out to the global scope. If the name isn't found anywhere, it throws a ReferenceError. Example:

var y = 24;
function favFunction() {
  var x = 667;
  var anotherFavFunction = function () {
    console.log(x);  // not in inner scope — found in favFunction
  };
  var yetAnotherFavFunction = function () {
    console.log(y);  // not in inner or favFunction — found in global scope
  };
  anotherFavFunction();
  yetAnotherFavFunction();
}
favFunction();

A closure is a function bundled together with the variables from the lexical scope in which it was defined. The inner function continues to have access to those variables even after the outer function has returned.

Example:

function randomFunc() {
  var obj1 = { name: "Vivian", age: 45 };
  return function () {
    console.log(obj1.name + " is awesome");  // still sees obj1
  };
}
var initialiseClosure = randomFunc();  // randomFunc has finished executing
initialiseClosure();                    // "Vivian is awesome"

Even though randomFunc has already returned by the time initialiseClosure() is called, the returned function still holds on to obj1. The garbage collector keeps obj1 alive because the closure references it.

Closures are the basis for many common JavaScript patterns: data privacy, partial application, memoization, and event handlers that need to remember some state.

A callback is a function passed as an argument to another function, with the intent that the receiving function will invoke it at some point — typically after completing some work.

Because functions are first-class values in JavaScript, you can pass them around the same way you pass strings or numbers.

Example:

function divideByHalf(sum) { console.log(Math.floor(sum / 2)); }
function multiplyBy2(sum)  { console.log(sum * 2); }

function operationOnSum(num1, num2, operation) {
  var sum = num1 + num2;
  operation(sum);
}

operationOnSum(3, 3, divideByHalf);  // 3
operationOnSum(5, 5, multiplyBy2);   // 20

Here operationOnSum takes a third argument — the callback — and decides when to invoke it. Callbacks are the foundation of asynchronous APIs in JavaScript: many older APIs (e.g. setTimeout, fs.readFile) take a callback that is invoked later, when the work is done.

Memoization is a form of caching in which the result of a function call is stored and reused the next time the function is called with the same arguments. It is primarily useful for pure, expensive functions, where calling them repeatedly with the same inputs is wasteful.

Consider a small (cheap) example:

function addTo256(num) { return num + 256; }
addTo256(20);  // 276
addTo256(40);  // 296
addTo256(20);  // 276 — recomputed unnecessarily

A memoized version stores results in a cache and consults it before recomputing:

function memoizedAddTo256() {
  var cache = {};
  return function (num) {
    if (num in cache) {
      console.log("cached value");
      return cache[num];
    }
    cache[num] = num + 256;
    return cache[num];
  };
}
var memoizedFunc = memoizedAddTo256();
memoizedFunc(20);  // computed
memoizedFunc(20);  // cached

The trade-off is memory: cached results have to live somewhere, so memoization is best applied to functions whose result space is bounded or whose recomputation is genuinely expensive.

Recursion is a programming technique in which a function calls itself to solve a smaller version of the same problem, eventually reaching a base case that doesn't recurse. A correct recursive function always has at least one base case and always reduces the problem size in each recursive call.

Example — sum of integers from n down to 0:

function add(number) {
  if (number <= 0) {
    return 0;          // base case
  }
  return number + add(number - 1);
}

Tracing add(3):
add(3) = 3 + add(2)
       = 3 + 2 + add(1)
       = 3 + 2 + 1 + add(0)
       = 3 + 2 + 1 + 0 = 6

Another example — sum of all elements in an array:

function computeSum(arr) {
  if (arr.length === 1) return arr[0];
  return arr.pop() + computeSum(arr);
}
computeSum([7, 8, 9, 99]);  // 123

Constructor functions are used to create multiple objects that share the same shape — the same set of properties and methods. By convention, the name of a constructor function starts with a capital letter (PascalCase), and you invoke it with the new keyword.

function Person(name, age, gender) {
  this.name = name;
  this.age = age;
  this.gender = gender;
}
var person1 = new Person("Vivek", 76, "male");
var person2 = new Person("Courtney", 34, "female");

When called with new, a new empty object is created, this inside the function is bound to that object, the constructor body runs (typically setting properties on this), and the new object is returned.

In modern JavaScript, the same pattern is more commonly written using the class syntax (introduced in ES6), which is syntactic sugar over constructor functions and the prototype chain.

Arrow functions, introduced in ES6, are a shorter syntax for writing function expressions. They cannot be used as constructors, do not have their own this, arguments, or super, and cannot be used as generators.

// Function expression
var add = function (a, b) { return a + b; };
// Arrow function
var arrowAdd = (a, b) => a + b;

If the body is a single expression, the braces and return keyword can be omitted. If there is exactly one parameter, the parentheses around the parameter list are also optional:

var multiplyBy2 = function (num) { return num * 2; };
var arrowMultiplyBy2 = num => num * 2;

The most important behavioral difference is the handling of this. An arrow function does not bind its own this — it inherits whatever this was in the enclosing lexical scope. Compare:

var obj1 = {
  valueOfThis: function () { return this; }
};
var obj2 = {
  valueOfThis: () => { return this; }
};
obj1.valueOfThis();  // obj1 — this depends on how the method was called
obj2.valueOfThis();  // the surrounding this (e.g. window in a browser script)

Before ES6, var was the only way to declare a variable. ES6 introduced let and const, which behave differently in several important ways:

| Feature              | var | let | const |
| -------------------- | --- | --- | ----- |
| Function scope       | yes | yes | yes   |
| Block scope          | no  | yes | yes   |
| Hoisted              | yes (initialized to undefined) | yes (TDZ) | yes (TDZ) |
| Added to window      | yes | no  | no    |
| Can be reassigned    | yes | yes | no    |
| Can be redeclared    | yes | no  | no    |

var vs let in the global scope: both are accessible anywhere, but only var becomes a property of the global window object:

var variable1 = 23;
let variable2 = 89;
window.variable1;  // 23
window.variable2;  // undefined

var vs let in function scope: behavior is the same — variables declared with either are confined to the enclosing function.

var vs let in block scope: var ignores blocks, let respects them:

{ var variable3 = [1, 2, 3, 4]; }
console.log(variable3);  // [1, 2, 3, 4]

{ let variable4 = [6, 55, -1, 2]; }
console.log(variable4);  // ReferenceError

for (let i = 0; i < 2; i++) { /* ... */ }
console.log(i);  // ReferenceError

const: behaves exactly like let except that the binding cannot be reassigned. The value itself isn't deeply frozen — if it is an object, its properties can still be mutated:

const x = { name: "Vivek" };
x = { address: "India" };  // TypeError
x.name = "Nikhil";          // OK
const y = 23;
y = 44;                       // TypeError

Both use the ... syntax, but they're used in opposite directions.

Rest parameter — used in a function's parameter list. It collects an arbitrary number of remaining arguments into a real array:

function extractingArgs(...args) {
  return args[1];
}
extractingArgs(8, 9, 1);  // 9

function addAllArgs(...args) {
  return args.reduce((sum, n) => sum + n, 0);
}
addAllArgs(6, 5, 7, 99);  // 117
addAllArgs(1, 3, 4);      // 8

The rest parameter must be the last parameter in the signature:

// Invalid:
function bad(a, ...args, c) { /* SyntaxError */ }
// Valid:
function good(a, b, ...args) { /* ... */ }

Spread operator — used in a function call, array literal, or object literal. It expands an iterable (or, for objects, the enumerable own properties) into individual elements:

function addFourNumbers(a, b, c, d) { return a + b + c + d; }
let fourNumbers = [5, 6, 7, 8];
addFourNumbers(...fourNumbers);  // 26

// Cloning and merging
let array1 = [3, 4, 5, 6];
let clonedArray1 = [...array1];                 // [3, 4, 5, 6]
let obj1 = { x: 'Hello', y: 'Bye' };
let obj2 = { z: 'Yes', a: 'No' };
let mergedObj = { ...obj1, ...obj2 };           // { x:'Hello', y:'Bye', z:'Yes', a:'No' }

Summary: rest gathers, spread distributes. Rest appears in a declaration, spread appears in a call or literal.

JavaScript offers several ways to create an object. The most common are:

Object literal:
var obj = { name: "Alice", age: 30 };

new Object() constructor:
var obj = new Object();
obj.name = "Alice";

Object.create() — creates a new object with the given prototype:
var obj = Object.create(somePrototype);

Constructor function with new:
function Person(name) { this.name = name; }
var p = new Person("Alice");

ES6 class (syntactic sugar over constructor functions):
class Person { constructor(name) { this.name = name; } }
var p = new Person("Alice");

Factory function — a plain function that returns an object literal:
function createPerson(name) { return { name }; }
var p = createPerson("Alice");

Promises represent the eventual result of an asynchronous operation. They were introduced as a better alternative to nesting callbacks ("callback hell") and give async code a flatter, more composable structure.

A promise is always in one of three states:

pending — the operation has not yet completed.

fulfilled — the operation completed successfully; the promise has a value.

rejected — the operation failed; the promise has a reason (typically an Error).

A promise is created with the Promise constructor, which takes an executor function with two callbacks: resolve (call on success) and reject (call on failure):

function sumOfThreeElements(...elements) {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    if (elements.length > 3) {
      reject("Only three elements or less are allowed");
    } else {
      let sum = elements.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0);
      resolve("Sum has been calculated: " + sum);
    }
  });
}

Consumers attach handlers with .then() (for fulfillment) and .catch() (for rejection):

sumOfThreeElements(4, 5, 6)
  .then(result => console.log(result))   // "Sum has been calculated: 15"
  .catch(error => console.log(error));

sumOfThreeElements(7, 0, 33, 41)
  .then(result => console.log(result))
  .catch(error => console.log(error));   // "Only three elements or less are allowed"

Modern code typically uses async/await, which is syntactic sugar over the same promise machinery.

Classes were introduced in ES6 as syntactic sugar over the existing prototype-based inheritance model. Under the hood, a class is still a constructor function plus a prototype — the syntax is just more familiar to programmers coming from languages like Java or C#.

Pre-ES6 (constructor function):

function Student(name, rollNumber, grade, section) {
  this.name = name;
  this.rollNumber = rollNumber;
  this.grade = grade;
  this.section = section;
}
Student.prototype.getDetails = function () {
  return `Name: ${this.name}, Roll no: ${this.rollNumber}, Grade: ${this.grade}, Section: ${this.section}`;
};
let student1 = new Student("Vivek", 354, "6th", "A");
student1.getDetails();

ES6 class:

class Student {
  constructor(name, rollNumber, grade, section) {
    this.name = name;
    this.rollNumber = rollNumber;
    this.grade = grade;
    this.section = section;
  }
  getDetails() {
    return `Name: ${this.name}, Roll no: ${this.rollNumber}, Grade: ${this.grade}, Section: ${this.section}`;
  }
}
let student2 = new Student("Garry", 673, "7th", "C");
student2.getDetails();

A few things worth knowing about classes:

Class declarations are not hoisted — you can't use a class before its declaration is reached.

Classes can extend other classes using the extends keyword and call into the parent with super.

Code inside a class body runs in strict mode automatically.

Generator functions, added in ES6, are a special kind of function that can pause execution and later resume from where it left off. They are declared with the function* syntax (note the asterisk) and use the yield keyword to produce values:

function* genFunc() {
  // ...
}

Calling a generator function does not run its body. Instead it returns a generator object that drives execution:

function* genFunc() {
  yield 3;
  yield 4;
}
genFunc();  // returns a Generator object — no code has run yet

Each call to the generator's next() method runs the function up to the next yield and returns an object of the form { value, done }:

var g = genFunc();
g.next();  // { value: 3, done: false }
g.next();  // { value: 4, done: false }
g.next();  // { value: undefined, done: true }

Generators are commonly used to implement custom iterators and lazy sequences. Example:

function* iteratorFunc() {
  let count = 0;
  for (let i = 0; i < 2; i++) {
    count++;
    yield i;
  }
  return count;
}
let iterator = iteratorFunc();
iterator.next();  // { value: 0, done: false }
iterator.next();  // { value: 1, done: false }
iterator.next();  // { value: 2, done: true }

A WeakSet is similar to a Set in that it stores a collection of unique values, but with two important differences:

It can only contain objects, not primitive values.

References to objects inside a WeakSet are weak. If the only reference to an object is the one held by the WeakSet, the object can still be garbage collected, at which point it silently disappears from the set.

Because entries can vanish at any time, WeakSet has a smaller API than Set: only add(), delete(), and has(). It is not iterable and has no size property.

const newSet = new Set([4, 5, 6, 7]);
console.log(newSet);                       // Set { 4, 5, 6, 7 }

const newSet2 = new WeakSet([3, 4, 5]);    // TypeError — primitives not allowed

let obj1 = { message: "Hello world" };
const newSet3 = new WeakSet([obj1]);
newSet3.has(obj1);                         // true

A WeakMap is like a Map (a collection of key/value pairs) with two important differences:

Keys must be objects — primitive values are not allowed.

The map holds its keys weakly: if no other reference to a key object exists, the key (and its associated value) can be garbage collected and will silently disappear from the map.

Because entries can vanish at any time, WeakMap is not iterable and has no size property. The only methods are get(), set(), has(), and delete().

const map1 = new Map();
map1.set('Value', 1);                  // OK

const map2 = new WeakMap();
map2.set('Value', 2.3);                // TypeError — keys must be objects

let obj = { name: "Vivek" };
const map3 = new WeakMap();
map3.set(obj, { age: 23 });            // OK

WeakMap is useful for associating data with an object without preventing the object from being garbage collected — for example, a cache keyed by DOM nodes.

Destructuring is a syntax for extracting values from arrays or properties from objects into distinct variables, all in a single statement.

Object destructuring — before ES6:

const classDetails = { strength: 78, benches: 39, blackBoard: 1 };
const classStrength   = classDetails.strength;
const classBenches    = classDetails.benches;
const classBlackBoard = classDetails.blackBoard;

The same code with destructuring:

const classDetails = { strength: 78, benches: 39, blackBoard: 1 };
const { strength: classStrength, benches: classBenches, blackBoard: classBlackBoard } = classDetails;
console.log(classStrength);   // 78
console.log(classBenches);    // 39
console.log(classBlackBoard); // 1

If you want the local variable to have the same name as the property, the rename syntax can be omitted:

const { strength } = classDetails;  // equivalent to const { strength: strength } = ...

Array destructuring — before ES6:

const arr = [1, 2, 3, 4];
const first  = arr[0];
const second = arr[1];
const third  = arr[2];
const fourth = arr[3];

With destructuring:

const arr = [1, 2, 3, 4];
const [first, second, third, fourth] = arr;

Destructuring also supports default values, the rest pattern, and works on function parameters, which makes it especially handy for functions that take an options object.

The Temporal Dead Zone (TDZ) is the period between when a let or const declaration is hoisted to the top of its block and when the declaration is actually executed. During that window the binding exists but cannot be read or written — any attempt throws a ReferenceError.

Examples:

x = 23;     // ReferenceError — x is in the TDZ
let x;

function anotherRandomFunc() {
  message = "Hello";  // ReferenceError — message is in the TDZ
  let message;
}
anotherRandomFunc();

The TDZ is the reason let and const are often described as "hoisted but not initialized" — the declaration is hoisted, but the binding remains in the TDZ until the declaration line is reached. var, in contrast, is initialized to undefined at the start of its scope, so reading it before the declaration line returns undefined instead of throwing.

var scope = "global scope";
function check() {
  var scope = "local scope";
  function f() {
    return scope;
  }
  return f;
}

check() returns the inner function f without calling it. Because f was defined inside check, it closes over check's local scope. Calling check()() therefore returns "local scope" — the global scope variable is shadowed by the local one that f sees through the closure. This is the canonical demonstration that JavaScript uses lexical (not dynamic) scoping.

// Code 1
function func1() {
  setTimeout(() => {
    console.log(x);
    console.log(y);
  }, 3000);
  var x = 2;
  let y = 12;
}
func1();

// Code 2
function func2() {
  for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
    setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 2000);
  }
}
func2();

// Code 3
(function () {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(1), 2000);
  console.log(2);
  setTimeout(() => console.log(3), 0);
  console.log(4);
})();

